## DTOs

- Use a DTO class for **every** input: body, query, and params
- Validate with `class-validator` decorators or Zod pipe ‚Äî never trust raw input
- Never accept `any` as a parameter or return type
- Keep DTOs in the presentation layer; map to Use Case input inside the controller

```ts
// ‚úÖ
@Post()
create(@Body() dto: CreateTodoDto) {
  return this.createTodoUseCase.execute(dto);
}

// ‚ùå
@Post()
create(@Body() body: any) { ... }
```

## HTTP Status Codes

Return semantically correct status codes:

| Code  | When                                                |
| ----- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| `200` | Successful GET, PATCH, PUT                          |
| `201` | Resource created                                    |
| `204` | Successful DELETE with no body                      |
| `400` | Validation error                                    |
| `401` | Unauthenticated                                     |
| `403` | Forbidden                                           |
| `404` | Resource not found                                  |
| `409` | Conflict (duplicate, state conflict)                |
| `500` | Unexpected server error (never for business errors) |

## Unified Error Format

All API errors return `ErrorResponseDto` via a global exception filter ‚Äî controllers must not format errors manually.

```ts
class ErrorResponseDto {
  statusCode: number;
  message: string | string[];
  error: string;
  timestamp: string;
  path: string;
}
```

- `message` ‚Äî human-readable text; use `string[]` for validation errors (one message per field)
- `error` ‚Äî short error name (e.g. `Bad Request`, `Not Found`)
- `timestamp` ‚Äî ISO 8601 string
- `path` ‚Äî request URL path

## Errors

### Never Throw Plain `Error`

Do not throw `new Error('...')` in application or domain code.

| Layer             | Exception type                                                   |
| ----------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Domain / Use Case | Domain exceptions (`TodoNotFoundError`, `InvalidTodoTitleError`) |
| Presentation      | NestJS HTTP exceptions mapped by a global filter                 |

```ts
// ‚úÖ domain
throw new TodoNotFoundError(todoId);

// ‚úÖ presentation filter maps to HTTP
throw new NotFoundException('Todo not found');

// ‚ùå
throw new Error('Todo not found');
```

### Domain Exceptions

- Live in the `domain/` layer
- Carry enough context for client messages
- Are mapped to HTTP status in the presentation layer ‚Äî not inside Use Cases

### HTTP Exceptions

- Use NestJS `HttpException` subclasses in controllers/filters when mapping domain errors
- Business rule violations ‚Üí `400` or `409`, not `500`
- Unexpected infrastructure failures ‚Üí `500`

